texts.html: Denver Broncos defensive end Derek Wolfe (95) during training camp at the Broncos training facility.(Photo: Chris Humphreys, USA TODAY Sports)
Denver Broncos defensive end Derek Wolfe was driven off the field at CenturyLink Field in Seattle after suffering a spine injury sustained in a helmet-to-helmet hit Saturday night.
text: Denver Broncos defensive end Derek Wolfe was driven off the field at CenturyLink Field in Seattle after suffering a spine injury sustained in a helmet-to-helmet hit Saturday night.

texts.html: Wolfe, the Broncos' second-round pick in 2012, had shed a low block when he collided with Seahawks fullback Michael Robinson.
text: Wolfe, the Broncos' second-round pick in 2012, had shed a low block when he collided with Seahawks fullback Michael Robinson.

texts.html: Wolfe was taken to a Seattle hospital, where results of a CT scan and MRI were negative, head coach John Fox said after the game.
text: Wolfe was taken to a Seattle hospital, where results of a CT scan and MRI were negative, head coach John Fox said after the game.

texts.html: Wolfe was released and allowed to fly home with the team late Saturday night.
text: Wolfe was released and allowed to fly home with the team late Saturday night.

texts.html: "So far, so good," Broncos head coach John Fox said. "We'll keep him in our prayers."
text: "So far, so good," Broncos head coach John Fox said. "We'll keep him in our prayers."

texts.html: Wolfe was just one of several starters who had to leave the 40-10 Seattle win with injuries. Cornerback Champ Bailey (foot), wide receiver Wes Welker (ankle), linebacker Stewart Bradley (wrist) and guard Louis Vasquez (knee) all were injured in the first half and did not return.
